6.5.13.3 — Axis 9: Cultural & Legal Intelligence (Absorbed from 6.5.11)
This axis is the full implementation of what was previously documented as Feature 6.5.11 — Regulatory-Aware Incident Reporting. It is renamed and expanded to reflect its true scope: a comprehensive destination briefing delivered after itinerary confirmation.

Cultural Norms Layer
•Greetings and social customs specific to each destination.
•Dress code requirements — religious sites, public spaces, specific regions within the country.
•Tipping culture — expected, discouraged, or absent.
•Photography restrictions — government buildings, military installations, religious sites, individuals.
•Bargaining norms — where expected, where considered offensive.
•Religious observances that affect public behavior, business hours, or access to services.
•Gender dynamics and safety considerations in specific regions.

Legal & Regulatory Layer
Stakes are real. Non-compliance with local law can result in fines, detention, deportation, or imprisonment. This layer is delivered as a calm pre-departure briefing — not a legal disclaimer, not a lecture.
•Visa requirements and entry conditions specific to the traveler's passport nationality.
•Customs regulations — prohibited imports/exports, declared items, duty thresholds.
•Medication that is legal at home but controlled or prohibited at destination. Common examples: certain ADHD medications, opioid-based pain relief, some anxiety medications.
•Local laws genuinely foreign to most travelers: drone regulations, alcohol laws, public conduct laws, LGBTQ+ legal status, cannabis laws, laws around photography of government infrastructure.
•Consequences stated plainly where they are severe — not to alarm but to inform.
•Visa-on-arrival eligibility, e-visa requirements, and common denial causes for the traveler's passport.

FRAMING REQUIREMENT:  Axis 9 output is never delivered as a warning or legal disclaimer. It is delivered as: "Here is what you need to know before you land in [destination]." Calm, specific, actionable. The traveler is treated as an intelligent adult who wants to be informed, not lectured.

Regulatory Incident Reporting (6.5.11 Function Preserved)
When a regulatory violation or border incident occurs during a trip, the platform supports structured incident documentation. This was the core function of 6.5.11 and is preserved here as an active feature of Axis 9 output.
•Incident type classification: entry denial, customs hold, visa issue, local law enforcement contact, mandatory quarantine, document confiscation.
•Documentation prompts: what to record, in what format, with what timestamps.
•Coverage implication: does any attached policy cover trip interruption, legal assistance, or emergency repatriation in this scenario?
•Embassy contact surfacing: nearest embassy or consulate for the traveler's nationality, with hours and emergency contact details.
•All regulatory incidents are logged to the Event Ledger per Section 8.4 standards.
INVARIANT AX9-1:  The platform does not provide legal advice for regulatory incidents. It documents, surfaces relevant contacts, and identifies coverage implications. The traveler is directed to their embassy and relevant insurer for legal and financial resolution.

6.5.13.4 — Axis 11: Authority-Driven Disruption Intelligence (Absorbed from 6.5.12)
This axis is the full implementation of what was previously documented as Feature 6.5.12 — Authority-Driven Travel Disruptions. It activates when signals indicate a government authority, security agency, or border authority is causing or is likely to cause itinerary disruption.

Signal Types That Activate Axis 11
Signal Type	What It Means for the Traveler	Coverage Implication
Security recheck requirement	Additional screening mandated by airport or border authority. Possible connection risk.	May trigger trip delay coverage depending on cause classification. Document the mandate in writing if possible.
Entry denial risk	Traveler's passport, visa, or documentation flagged as potentially ineligible at destination.	Trip cancellation coverage may apply. Depends on whether entry denial was foreseeable at time of purchase.
Border closure	Land, air, or sea entry point closed by government authority.	Trip interruption coverage likely applies. Document official closure notice.
Government travel restriction	Destination country or transit country has issued a restriction affecting the traveler's nationality or route.	Force majeure implications. Coverage varies by policy language — check Axis 2 output.
Embassy shelter-in-place advisory	Embassy recommending or ordering nationals to shelter. May require immediate itinerary change.	Trip interruption and emergency evacuation coverage triggered in most policies. Document advisory timestamp.
Airport/port security incident	Active security event affecting departure or arrival facility.	Coverage cascade identical to standard disruption — Axis 7 disruption narrative applies with authority classification.

How Axis 11 Interacts with the Causality Model
Authority-driven disruptions get a specific cause_class_internal value in the Causality Object: EXTERNAL with cause_label_public of "Government Restriction." This classification matters because:
•Some policies cover Government Restriction events that standard trip cancellation would not.
•Airlines may invoke force majeure exemptions — reducing their obligation — but the traveler's insurance may still respond.
•The platform surfaces the classification and its coverage implications without determining the outcome.
All Axis 11 activations are logged as causality events per Section 3.4 and emit a platform alert to the traveler.

6.5.13.5 — Vulnerability Resolution Layer
MVP Posture: Full Inclusion
At MVP launch, the Vulnerability Resolution Layer is included in the Deep Scan price. Finding and solving is one product. The traveler sees a gap and immediately receives what closes it.
Resolution output includes:
•Identification of each vulnerability by axis and clause basis.
•Category of coverage that addresses each gap — not a specific product recommendation, a coverage type.
•What to ask for when contacting a broker, insurer, or carrier.
•Documentation checklist: what to prepare before departure if the gap is not closed.
•Pre-departure action sequence: the order in which to address each vulnerability.
BROKER LINE COMPLIANCE:  The Resolution Layer does not recommend specific products, insurers, or policies. It identifies gap categories and tells the traveler what to ask for. This framing keeps the platform on the correct side of the insurance broker licensing boundary in all jurisdictions.

Phase 2+ Posture: Subscription Differentiation
•Per-trip Deep Scan (à la carte): Full 10-axis diagnosis + basic resolution suggestions.
•Subscriber Deep Scan (Protected Pro and above): Full diagnosis + full guided resolution including specific action sequences, documentation prep, and pre-departure checklist.
Users are informed of this transition at MVP launch. No one loses something they currently have.

